%N A082897 Perfect totient numbers.
%C A082897 It is trivial that perfect totient numbers must be odd. It is easy to show that powers of 3 are perfect totient numbers.
%C A082897 The product of the first n Fermat primes (A019434) is also a perfect totient number. There are 57 terms under 10^11. - _Jud McCranie_, Feb 24 2012
%C A082897 Terms 15, 255, 65535 and 4294967295 also belong to A051179 (see Theorem 4 in Loomis link). - _Michel Marcus_, Mar 19 2014
%C A082897 For the first 64 terms, a(n) is approximately 1.56^n. - _Jud McCranie_, Jun 17 2017
%C A082897 These numbers were first studied in 1939 by the Spanish mathematician Laureano Pérez-Cacho Villaverde (1900-1957). The term "perfect totient number" was coined by Venkataraman (1975). - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 10 2021
